		<category><![CDATA[florida]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Jackson]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Medical Marijuana]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[michigan]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[norml]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[weed]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://badgals-radio.com/?p=11063</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Today Was April 20th &#8211; a universal day of Ganja Appreciation. We celebrated along with everyone else by visiting our favorite dispensary, and getting our favorite strains at a slight discount; due to a promotion for the day. We received the text early this morning and when we arrived the wait was well over 30 [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><img class="aligncenter" src="http://www.miller-mccune.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/mmw-medical-marijuana-100711.jpg" alt="" /></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Today Was April 20th &#8211; a universal day of Ganja Appreciation. We celebrated along with everyone else by visiting our favorite dispensary, and getting our favorite strains at a slight discount; due to a promotion for the day. We received the text early this morning and when we arrived the wait was well over 30 minutes, with two rooms working at the same time.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">They were once again able to accept credit cards, which meant most folks including me could spend fairly liberally &#8211; since it was a holiday. the festivities included folks saying <em>Happy Four Twenty</em>, and <em>Get Blazed</em>. Of course we chimed right in and sent out our friendly cyber spliff, which we received back late in the evening; after much passing and puffing.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">The thing about today&#8217;s cyber spliff is that you really have to hit it before you pass it on. yeah, you know that means alot of folks were medicating all over the place.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Can you imagine how much money was spent on Marijuana Today ? hey remember this is the so called <em>Stoners Christmas</em> &#8211; and people celebrate like it&#8217;s a holiday because it only comes once a year.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">We believe that everyone should have the right to medicate in the manner that they choose; based upon your beliefs and legal status. In Michigan the fight is in deep drama mode. But why ?</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Is it the intention of the sitting government that Medical Marijuana should be legislated out of availability to Patients ?</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Apparently so, because they are shutting down dispensaries; destroying grow ops; and interfering with patient caregiver exchanges state wide.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">In Jackson the community is strong and activism is in full effect, by both patients, and caregivers. The city government has had their issues with clarity on the law and enforcement; but lately they seem ready to accept that Patients and Caregivers are not criminals.</p>
<p><strong>We received a short update from our friend Blueberry tonight.<em> Dig This,</em></strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Dear badgal,</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">First,  I wanted to give you folks an update in the market.  The Jackson Market is operating with the full knowledge and approval of the city of Jackson.  We are compliant with all local and state law.   The City understands our mission.  We have educated them that we fill a vital position in the community.   We are unique in that we are compassion based and non profit.  The market is located at 135 West Pearl in Jackson, MI.  The market opens from 12 to 4 every Sat. and Sunday.  The market remain safe.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">The ruling from the appeals court is troubling on many levels.  A person can test positive for cannabis use for up to 30 days.  This new ruling means that if you are tested, whether you are impaired or not, you can be convicted.  It might have been two weeks since you medicated, but they can still convict you.  Even more troubling to me, it is a Section 7 violation.  Which nullifies the medical marijuana defense.  Which means you could be prosecuted under the PHC or the CSA for possession.  It was a terrible ruling and places all of us in danger.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">We were successful in stopping the four bills and educating the public as to the danger to patients.   My concern is when I hear CPU talking about fixing the Bills.  Hearing them talking about having so much work in, that they don’t want the Bills to die.  This is insane folks.  The whole idea is to try to  preserve our freedom, not to save  CPU wasted efforts at over turning the act.  They were responsible for the Bills to start with.  They say as much themselves.  They were also responsible for reaching compromises before the committee vote.   Without their approval those Bills would not have made it to the vote on the 29th of March.  Now, that we have delayed the vote again, they are again talking about  fixing the Bills.  These folks have failed miserably and are desperate.  That is a recipe for disaster.  They continue too insist on repeating their  mistakes.  That is the definition of insanity.  Write your Reps today and tell them that CPU does not represent you. !</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">The email-omatic is still up and running.  Don’t delay.    <a href="http://mmma.co/email/MMMA_minorml_email_form_letter1.html" target="_blank">http://mmma.co/email/MMMA_<wbr>minorml_email_form_letter1.<wbr>html</wbr></wbr></a></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">We  have a protest scheduled for May 29th to protest the appeals court decision as well as the pending legislation.  We urge you to go to the protest Facebbok page and join.  Please use the facebook tool to invite all of your friends.  We must build an army to stop these civil rights violations.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"> The Facebook Page is located at <a href="https://www.facebook.com/events/312712545467695/314041402001476/?notif_t=like" target="_blank">https://www.facebook.com/<wbr>events/312712545467695/<wbr>314041402001476/?notif_t=like</wbr></wbr></a></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Thanks,</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Blueberry</p>
</blockquote>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Michigan and Florida concern me greatly, because both are huge patient populations that are under attack. One legal &#8211; Michigan, about to loose it&#8217;s legality. and the other Florida, fighting tooth and nail to prevent legality for patients and caregivers.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">It&#8217;s clear that in GOP states the profit factor is ignored, in favor of prohibition to patients. This is both anti humanitarian and anti profit. Big studies of the underground market, produced data that gave clarity to todays&#8217; dispensary operations budgets. no one could have believed that this much money could flow legally into the system, from the dispensation of alternative medications.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Big Pharma wants to do as much as it can to keep Medical Marijuana illegal, and they lobby hard in congress to do just that. In each state the situation is much the same, unless the community of patients and caregivers unite to form a clear voice.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">This has happened in Michigan and it&#8217;s shaken the Snyder government enough, that they&#8217;ve continued to hold meetings on legality of Dispensaries and Caregiver Exchange Programs. This is signifigant because it says clearly that some recognition of the programs exist, and must be clarified in future amendments of Michigans Medical Marijuana Act.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">We&#8217;ve got our irons in the fire in Florida, and we&#8217;re watching them heat up. We can see that the Scott government, much like the Snyder government has reservations based purely on social and moral objections; not legality. This is how the legalization fight has been left to mire for more than 10 years.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">We can personally say that we&#8217;ve seen the state of Florida and their enforcement and wildlife officers going after personal gardens; which they claim violate the state law. But there is no state law saying you can&#8217;t grow your own if you have a legal reason. Many Rastafarians in Florida have been harrassed and had their crops confiscated for just this madness. Even though they have been to the US Supreme Court to clarify that Marijuana is their rightful sacrament. The USSC accepted it, so the state of Florida needs to accept it too.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Sooner or later the economics of the situation will become the real meat; and only then will we see some meaningful federal action. There needs to be a consistent comparison in the growth of the Medical Marijuana market.  If the federal government could finally see that their prosecution of small amounts amounts to both health and religious persecution.  The USSC has ruled that both are illegal under the present constitution.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">As bad as the US Economy is you would think the gop would finally see the green, instead of all that red they created.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">America Take A Good Deep Toke of This Truth, and Demand Decriminalization Now. Stop harassing patients and caregivers.  End the Prohibition on Marijuana TODAY,</p>
<p><img class="size-medium wp-image-6943 alignleft" title="re-sig-redline" src="http://badgals-radio.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/re-sig-redline-300x92.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="92" /></p>
]]></content:encoded>
